<head>
<title>DEA-Lockerbie Link</title>
<!-- Place: Lockerbie, Scotland (UK) -->
<!-- Time: late 1988 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>DEA May Be Involved In Lockerbie Disaster</h1>

<p>From <a href="/revolution/by_name/H/MalcolmHutty.html">Malcolm
Hutty</a>:</p>

<p>I am currently listening to a BBC Radio 4 interview with an ex-DEA
official named Lester Coleman. He claims that the Pan-Am airliner which
was blown up over <a
href="/revolution/by_place/Europe/UK/Lockerbie.html">Lockerbie</a>, Scotland,
killing 200+ was not bombed by
Libyan terrorists but probably by Lebanese drug smugglers and terrorists
approved by the DEA.</p>

<p>He used to run a DEA/CIA joint operation in Frankfurt. The operation was
to approve the smuggling of drugs on American planes into America.  These
drugs could then be traced, allowing the DEA to find and capture American
importers, distributors and dealers. His office co-ordinated the
smuggling through third-party countries that the plane would land in en
route to the States, assuring the Drug Enforcement officials of those
countries that the drugs were being transferred through and would not end
up in their country. </p>

<p>18 months before the bombing, the ground operative of the DEA in Syria and
a friend of his were shot. He suspected that the Lebanese terrorists and
smugglers working in Syria found out that they were being used by the DEA.
He reported back to his supervisors in the States, who told him to pack up
and get out. He returned to America, where he was debriefed and
transferred to other duties. Since then he has been fired, and after a
court action (sorry, I didn't catch what for) he has been charged with
perjury. Since then he has discovered that his operation in Frankfurt was
restarted after his recall home. </p>

<p> He claims that in his experience the Libyan government would not have the
intelligence capability to plant a bomb on the Pan Am airliner. His
experience was as working as a DIA operative in Tripoli. </p>

<p> On the other hand the Lebanese working through their allies the Syrians
had the capability and the opportunity. The DEA sees them as drug
smugglers -- that is their worth to the DEA -- but they are primarily
terrorists with a political and religious agenda, using drug smuggling to
finance their operations. </p>

<p> Coleman says that security at Frankfurt and Heathrow airports, where the
doomed airliner stopped, is normally very tight, and it would take an
extremely effective unit to get a bomb through. It is most likely, in his
judgement, that the package that was a bomb was waived through by the DEA
operation that he used to belong to under the mistaken belief that it was
a drug consignment. After all, that must have been the belief of the
courier who took it onto the flight and got blown up with it. </p>

<p> After the interview with him the interviewer said that the Lockerbie 
police unit, the Crown Prosecution Service, the Foreign Office, the Home 
Office (responsible for, <cite>inter alia</cite>, MI5 the home intelligence 
service and liaison with similar services in other friendly nations like 
the DEA), HM Customs and Excise, and the Frankfurt police have produced 
almost identical "No comment" statements, saying that "in the light of the 
pending prosecution of two (Libyan) men for the bombing it would be 
inappropriate to comment or to co-operate with a programme in which 
opinions as to the guilt or innocence of these men might be canvassed"
Under British law such comment is <cite>sub judice</cite>, i.e. illegal. No
First Amendment here.</p>

<p> There was also a telephone interview with an academic, Dr. Squire. He
said nothing except that it was extremely plausible, especially when you
look at the passage in Mrs. Thatcher's recently published memoirs which
say ...  -- at which point the phone went dead. The interviewer said "Dr
Squire? We appear to have lost Dr Squire. In today's European Union summit
the GATT was the centre of attention...". He came back later to say that all
people who had any information relating to the bombing should contact the
Lockerbie police, and having said that the Thatcher memoirs were particularly
interesting on this issue because ... I'm sorry Dr Squire, that is all we've
got time for.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
