<html>
<head>
<title>Gorman Runs For Speaker</title>
<!-- Place: announcement Concord, New Hampshire (USA) -->
<!-- Time: announcement May 1, 1996 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Libertarian Legislator Seeks Speaker Role</h1>

<p><a href="/revolution/by_name/L/LPUS.html">Libertarian</a> state
legislator
<a href="/revolution/by_name/G/DonGorman.html">Don Gorman</a> announced
in May 1996 that he is running for Speaker
of the <a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/nh/">New Hampshire</a>
House. The 400-member House will elect a new speaker in mid-December 1996.</p>

<p>Gorman's strategy is to assemble a coalition of Democrats, who lack
the votes to elect one of their own as Speaker; disaffected Republicans;
and any new Libertarian legislators elected in November. If elected,
Gorman promises to:</p>

<ul>
<li>Give the State & Federal Relations Committee "the new charge of 
ending unconstitutional Federal mandates.
<li>"Create a Sunset Committee to reduce and streamline our cluttered 
and cumbersome RSAs [state laws.]"
<li>"Strengthen the involvement and participation of every member."
</ul>

<p>Gorman has spent eight years as a member of the N.H. House; 1993 to 
1996 as a Libertarian, and 1973 to 1976 as a Republican.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: May 8, 1996 advisory from the
<a href="/revolution/by_name/L/LPUS.html">Libertarian Party</a>.</p>

