<html>

<head>
<title>Jerome Tuccille</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Jerome Tuccille</h1>

<p>Jerome Tuccille was one of the early leaders of the modern libertarian
movement. He wrote in several libertarian journals before the
<a href="/revolution/by_name/L/LPUS.html">Libertarian Party</a>
was established and became active in the party when it was.</p>

<p>Tuccille was the
<a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/lpny/">Free Libertarian Party
of New York's</a> 1974 gubernatorial
candidate. He garnered publicity by sending a blonde in a body suit riding
through Central Park on a horse named Taxpayer. <cite>Newsweek</cite> said
Tuccille "hardly believes in government at all," noting his support for the
free market; legalizing prostitution, abortion and drugs; and ending taxes,
subsidies, tariffs, quotas, land use controls and antidiscrimination laws.</p>

<p>In the 1980's Tuccille went on to become an investment author. His
son, J.D. Tuccille (<img src="/images/mail.gif" alt="[EMAIL]"><a
href="mailto:tooch@aol.com">tooch@aol.com</a>) is also a writer, currently
an editor with the online version of the New York <cite>Daily News</cite>.</p>

<p>Appearances in <b>Revolution</b>:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/magarts.html">
	Magazine articles on the libertarianism</a></li>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/history.html">
	History of the Libertarian Party</a></li>
</ul>

