<head>
<title>1984 LP Campaigns</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: election November 1984 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>1984 Libertarian Election Results</h1>

<ul>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/lpil/givot.html">Givot for
	Senate</a>: 60,000 votes (1.25%)</li>
<li>Bergland/Lewis for President/Vice President: 228,314 votes.</li>
</ul>

<h2>1984 Libertarian Presidential Campaign</h2>

<p>The 1983 Libertarian national convention nominated <a
href="/revolution/by_name/B/DavidBergland.html">David Bergland</a> for
President and <a href="/revolution/by_name/L/JimLewis.html">Jim Lewis</a>
for Vice President. Bergland was a Coast Mesa,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ca/">California</a> lawyer,
had been the Libertarian 1976 vice presidential candidate,
and served as party chair from 1977 to 1981. Lewis was a salesman and
tax protestor.</p>

<p>Radio talk show host Gene Burns had been the frontrunner for the
presidential nomination, but withdrew a week before the convention when
he decided the party didn't have enough funding for a strong campaign.</p>

<p>The delegates quickly centered around Bergland as representative of
the party's radical wing, and Earl Ravenal as representative of
the more moderate Cato Institute-oriented wing. After Ravenal lost,
many of his supporters left the party.</p>

<p>Many states tightened ballot access laws after strong independent and
Libertarian showings in the
<a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/election/1980/">1980 presidential
election</a>. The Bergland/Lewis
ticket was on 40 ballots and won 228,314 votes. This was the first and
so far only time the Libertarian Party presidential candidate had the
third highest candidate vote total. (The party has had the third highest
party total -- excluding independents -- for most elections.)</p>

<hr>

<p>Sources:</p>
Richard Brookhiser's "Saving the UOS," <cite>National Review</cite>,
35:1274; <cite>Facts on File</cite>, 21 December 1984, 967 B1.</p>

