<head>
<title>U.S. Card</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: report 1994 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>The U.S. Card Proposal</h1>

<p>The May 1994 <cite>Digital Media: A Seybold Report</cite>
(<img src="/images/mail.gif" alt="[EMAIL]"><a
href="mailto:dmedia@netcom.com">dmedia@netcom.com</a>) reported on
a Clinton administration plan to create a national identity card.</p>

<p>Mitch Ratcliffe (<img src="/images/mail.gif" alt="[EMAIL]"><a
href="mailto:godsdog@netcom.com">godsdog@netcom.com</a>), Editor in Chief,
reported that several government agencies revealed their plans at
the April 1994 CardTech/SecureTech Conference, held to discuss "smart card"
and PCMCIA card applications for business and government.</p>

<p>The Postal Service presented a proposal for a "general purpose U.S.
services smartcard," which Ratcliffe said "individuals and companies would
use to authenticate their identities when sending and receiving electronic
mail, transferring funds and interacting with government agencies, such as
the I.R.S., Veterans Administration and the Department of Health and Human
Services."</p>

<p>Other government entities, including Hillary Clinton's health care task
force and the I.R.S, are considering national identity cards. The Postal
Service is trying to convince the federal government to use a single card
approach. The Postal Service project was actually initiated by the Department
of Defense, with consulting along the way from the National Security Agency.</p>

<p>The Postal Service's "U.S. Card" could be used as an electronic
authentication method for secure transactions. Coincidentally, and especially
combined with the Clipper Chip proposal, this would give the federal
government access to a huge amount of information about individuals and
companies that use the card.</p>

