<html>
<head>
<title>Kashmir</title>
<!-- Place: Kashmir, India and Pakistan -->
<!-- Time: 1947 - 1996+ -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Kashmir</h1>

<p>The countries of
<a href="/revolution/by_place/Asia/India/">India</a> and
<a href="/revolution/by_place/Asia/Pakistan/">Pakistan</a> were formed
at the end of
<a href="/revolution/by_place/Europe/UK/">British</a> colonial rule
in the area in 1947. Neither country was
too happy about the boundaries formed in the Kashmir region,
and since then they have fought two wars and engaged in numerous
skirmishes over it.</p>

<p>Jammu-Kashmir is India's part and the only majority Muslim state
in India. Separatist rebels, supported at least symbolically by
the Pakistani government, have waged a war in which 12,000 people have
died since 1989.</p>

<p>In the mid-1990's, fighting between the two countries increased,
although not to the point of a full-scale war. In January and February
1996, 25 people were killed, twenty of them when a rocket hit a
mosque. Each side blames the other for the rocket.</p>

<p>India is believed to have nuclear missiles, and Pakistan is believed
to be capable of building nuclear missiles. On January 27, 1996, ignoring
international criticism, India test-fired a ballistic missile with a
range of 155 miles and capable of carrying a nuclear payload. Strong
political forces in India advocate a nuclear build-up and testing.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: February 5, 1996 Associated Press article, "Tension mounts
between archenemies India and Pakistan," reprinted in the
<a href="/revolution/by_name/N/NandO.html">NandO Times</a>.</p>

