<html>
<head>
<title>Taiwan</title>
<!-- Place: China, Taiwan -->
<!-- Time: 1949 - present; missile tests March 1996 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Taiwan</h1>

<p><a href="/revolution/by_place/Asia/China/">China</a> is a good example
of how disastrous bad ideas can be. The
Chinese are extraordinarily successful everywhere in the world --
except mainland China. In 1949, Communists seized power in the
mainland, causing the ruling Nationalists to flee to the island
of Taiwan.</p>

<p>Since then, the People's Republic China has implemented a communist state,
while the Republic of China (the Taiwanese government) has implemented
a fairly free-market state. China's economic performance has been only
slightly better than dismal, while Taiwan has become one of the economic
powerhouses of the Asia-Pacific rim.</p>

<p>China considers Taiwan a renegade province, and maintains that
it will never allow Taiwan to declare independence. China has not
invaded Taiwan because of its formidable 400,000-person military
including a strong air force, navy and missile capability.</p>

<h2>Tensions in the 1990s</h2>

<p>In summer 1995, Taiwan began making more movement towards independence,
having its president visit foreign countries. After that, China began
conducting more military exercises near Taiwan.</p>

<p>In March 1996, tensions reached a new high when China began
extensive sea and air exercises very near Taiwan, even firing three
surface-to-surface missiles into waters near Taiwan's two main ports
of Kaohsiung and Keelong. China intended to scare Taiwanese voters
from electing a pro-independence president.</P>

<hr>

<p>Source: March 8, 1996 Associated Press article, "Taiwan threatens action
if China enters waters during missile tests," reprinted in the
<a href="/revolution/by_name/N/NandO.html">NandO Times</a>.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
