<head>
<title>Sri Lankan Civil War</title>
<!-- Place: Sri Lanka -->
<!-- Time: civil war started 1983;
	govt takes Jaffna December 1995;
	major offensive launched April 1996 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Yet Another Ethnic Separatist War</h1>

<p>One of humanity's favorite pastimes over the millenia of recorded
history, and probably before that as well, has been wars of ethnic
separation. The fairly recent advent of civilization has helped matters
somewhat, but even nations that aren't plagued with ethnic conflict
find themselves compelled to interfere in such disputes.</p>

<p>Just in case the U.S. or U.N. ever decides to cast its eye on
Sri Lanka, I'll put up a little background on that particular
exercise in futility.</p>

<p>Sri Lanka is an island country off the coast of India. Sri Lanka
has two main ethnic groups, the Sinhala (who control the government)
and the Tamils (who don't). The Tamils one day decided they
wanted to have their own country with a backyard and white picket fence,
and hence were born the Tamil Tiger guerrillas. I'm not sure, but
I think the Tamil's main grievance is that it is too hard to pronounce
"Sri".</p>

<p>The Tamils started their civil war in 1983, and as of 1996, are
still at it. The Sri Lankan government has launched many offensives
against the rebels, and in December 1995 scored big points by
taking the town of Jaffna, a rebel stronghold.</p>

<p>The Sri Lankan government estimates more than 50,000 people have
been killed in the 13-year war.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: March 25, 1996 Reuter Information Service news article,
"Sri Lankan forces, rebels prepare for new offensive," reprinted in the
<a href="/revolution/by_name/N/NandO.html">NandO Times</a>.</p>

