<head>
<title>Dugway Proving Ground</title>
<!-- Time: 1951 - 1969; sheep killed 1968 -->
<!-- Place: Dugway, Utah (USA) -->
</head>

<h1>U.S. Military Conducted Open-air Biowarfare Experiments</h1>

<p>A December 8, 1994 staff report prepared for the U.S. Senate Committee on
Veterans' Affairs included a description of the U.S. military's open-air
experiments with hazardous chemical and biological agents.</p>

<p>From 1951 to 1969, the U.S. military conducted hundreds or perhaps
thousands of such tests at
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ut/Dugway.html">Dugway
Proving Ground</a> near Salt Lake City,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ut/">Utah</a>.
In one case, Venezuelan equine encephalomyelitis (VEE) was found in the
nearby animal population. In 1968, over six thousand sheep died
following the release of a nerve gas from an airplane. The Department of
Defense initially blamed the deaths on pesticide use, but after autopsies
found a nerve agent, the Department reimbursed the ranchers whose sheep
were poisoned.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
