<html>

<head>
<title>Infowar</title>
<!-- Place: global -->
<!-- Time: 1990s -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Infowar</h2>

<p>Military strategists are contemplating a new form of warfare arising
out of the computer-driven, information-based economy of today.</p>

<p>Advanced societies rely on telecommunications networks, electronics
equipment and information for the coordination of critical industries
and for warfare. Infowar, the disruption of these information channels,
is foreseen to become commonplace in the near future.</p>

<p>"Infowar" is evolving from the psych-ops and disinformation campaigns
of the twentieth century. In addition to leafletting, broadcasting and
other more established methods of information warfare, armies will use
computer viruses, network hacking, encryption cracking and frequency
jamming to wreak havoc on the other side's military operations, financial
institutions, media, transportation and other critical areas.</p>

<p>Such techniques will become more prominent as battlefield equipment
advances in technology. Future soldiers will be wearing helmets that
include microphones, earphones, night-vision goggles and a heads-up
battlefield display. Defeating such gadgetry through jamming or
disinformation will be a crucial component of infowar.</p>

<p>Infowar will also include battle simulations. Computer simulations may
convince strategists whether to fight or not. Entire wars could be fought
virtually, with the participants skipping to the peace treaty based on the
probable outcome as predicted by computers.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: October 15, 1995 <cite>Times</cite> of London article "Dawn of
the cyber soldiers" reprinted in the <cite>News and Observer</cite>.</p>

