<head>
<title>U.N. Budget Crisis</title>
<!-- Place: global -->
<!-- Time: 1996 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>U.N. Almost as Financially Bankrupt as Morally</h1>

<p>In February 1996, the <a href="index.html">United Nations</a>
had a two-year budget of $2.6 billion, but faced a financial crisis
that may cause it to lay off some of its 13,000 leeches, I mean
professional and clerical employees, to prevent bankruptcy.
A U.N. advisory panel
recommended cutting 600 general nonprofessional staff (10% of
the total) and 550 professional staff (14%), freezing recruitment,
and not renewing short-term employment contracts.</P>

<p>Member countries "owed" the U.N. $2.1 billion at the end of 1995,
over half of that from the
<A href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/">United States</a> alone.
U.N. dues are based
on "from each according to his ability" such that U.S. payments make
up 25% of the total.</p>

<p>Some U.N. proponents advocate a global income tax as a way to
reduce U.N. "dependency" on member governments.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: February 5, 1996 Reuter Information Service article,
"UN considers cutting 1,100 staff in budget crisis," reprinted in
the <a href="/revolution/by_name/N/NandO.html">NandO Times</a>.</p>

