<head>
<title>Credit Cards in Belize</title>
<!-- Place: Belize -->
<!-- Time: May 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Credit Card Privacy</h1>

<p>Excerpts from an anonymous post to Libernet in May 1995:</p>

<p>I trashed the <a href="/revolution/by_name/T/TerraLibra.html">Terra Libra</a>
project some months ago. You might remember the
description of a flat pyramid marketing scheme where you "sell freedom
technology."  They also are pushing a gold-based banking system that looks like
it may be enjoying some success. The most useful aspect I have seen so far from
the project is a low-cost offshore trust offer.</p>

<p>Terra Libra now has the offshore account based in Belize, where a recent
supreme court decision "upheld the country's confidentiality laws by revoking a
previous court order set in motion by the SEC of the US requesting that
confidential documents, belonging to Swiss Trade and Commerce Trust, Ltd., be
handed over to them."  It looks like little Belize stood up to the SEC and will
now become a banking haven in the traditional Bahamian manner.</p>

<p>It takes $800 to set one of these accounts up for yourself, or as little as
$200 with three other sign-ups, and, again, it starts with $200 in it so your
effective cost will be as little as $0 and as much as $600 if you do not want
to participate in the multi-level marketing scheme.</p>

<p>There is a big difference now, though.  You can use a credit card, Visa I
think, to access your account by charging items and getting cash advances all
over the world.  It has a limit equal to the account balance in your offshore
account, and the payments to the credit account may be made by the trust
automatically.  The charge for having your trust make the payments is 5% of the
amount or $10, whichever is less.  There is also a minimum account balance of
$1100 to begin the credit account with a $1000 limit, which of course may be
increased, and you get up to three cards free.</p>

<p>The account is numbered and your name is not associated with the account. 
The credit card is "completely confidential, no social security number or
credit information is required."</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: May 13, 1995 posting to Libernet by an43931@anon.penet.fi.</p>

