<head>
<title>Astrophysicist Busted</title>
<!-- Place: resident of Tucson, Arizona (USA) -->
<!-- Time: arrest September 8, 1993;
	sentencing hearing November 20, 1994;
	imprisoned August 25, 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Astrophysicist gets 5 years for first pot offense</h1>

<p>Steven Pearce, an astrophysicist and <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/Canada/">Canadian</a> citizen, was
sentenced to a mandatory minimum of five years in prison for attempting to
transport forty pounds of marijuana.</p>

<p>Pearce completed his Ph.D. at the University of Arizona at
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/az/Tucson.html">Tucson</a>,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/az/">Arizona</a>, where
he worked with Dr. Eugene Levy at the Lunar and Planetary Laboratory. He has
authored and co-authored many scientific papers in peer-reviewed journals.</p>

<p>On September 8, 1993, Pearce was arrested for transporting 40 pounds of
marijuana. He was trying to make enough money to pay child support he owed.
The nonviolent crime was Pearce's first offense.</p>

<p>Under mandatory minimum sentencing guidelines, the judge was forced to
sentence Pearce to five years of prison, two years of supervised probation,
1000 hours of community service and a $15,000 fine. Pearce will be
deported when he is released.</p>

<p>Pearce's probation officer and judge both believed Pearce should get a
lesser sentence, but were unable to alter the mandatory minimum. The judge
granted Pearce an unsupervised five-month stay of execution of sentence to
allow him to complete his dissertation, and later extended the stay another
five months.</p>

<p>On August 25, 1995, Pearce will enter prison.</p>

<p>Source: August 7, 1995 forward to Libernet originally by
David Borden (<img src="/images/mail.gif" alt="[EMAIL]"><a
href="mailto:borden@netcom.com">borden@netcom.com</a>) of <a
href="/revolution/by_name/D/DRCNet.html">DRCNet</a>.</p>

