<html>
<head>
<title>John Doe #2</title>
<!-- Place: Oklahoma City, Oklahoma (USA) -->
<!-- Time: April 19, 1995; October 26, 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>John Doe #2</h1>

<p>Immediately after the <a href="index.html">April 19, 1995 bombing</a> of
the Alfred R. Murrah Federal Building in <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ok/OklahomaCity.html">Oklahoma
City</a>, <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ok/">Oklahoma</a>, federal
investigators released sketches of two suspects, initially identified only
as John Doe #1 and John Doe #2.</p>

<p>Investigators later arrested Timothy McVeigh, claiming he was John Doe
#1.</p>

<p>However, no arrests have been made for John Doe #2, and investigators
have even denied his existence, despite mounting evidence that there was
another person involved. Authorities said that an innocent Army private
resembled the sketches, but never withdrew the sketches.</p>

<h2>Grand juror dismissed</h2>

<p><a href="/revolution/by_name/D/DavidDeming.html">David Deming</a>
reported that a juror was dismissed from the grand jury on October 26, 1995,
for questioning the prosecutors.</p>

<p>According to Deming, "This particular person had revealed that the jury
was essentially being manipulated by the prosecution, and they were not
allowed to follow leads to the mysterious John Doe #2, or call witnesses
to testify who had seen JD2 in the company of Mr. McVeigh."</p>

<p>Deming continued, "Oklahoma City television station KFOR (channel 4) has
now, at the last count, interviewed 12 (count 'em, twelve) eyewitnesses who
spotted JD2 either with McVeigh or close to his wherabouts. They also have
2 eyewitnesses who have appeared on camera who spotted a total of 4 people
(McVeigh, plus JD2, plus 2 others) in front of the Murrah building only
minutes before the blast."</p>

<h2>Videotape shows second person</h2>

<p>On October 27, 1995, the Associated Press reported that a surveillance
camera captured an image of a passenger -- "perhaps the long-sought John
Doe #2" -- in the Ryder truck that blew up the federal building.</p>

<p>The AP interviewed a law enforcement source who said that the camera
showed an unidentifiable and shadowy image of a person in the passenger
seat about three minutes before the federal building was bombed.</p>

<p>The AP quoted the source as saying that many investigors believe John
Doe #2 is still at large. "No one knows who he is, it's like he walked into
a wall and vanished," the source said.</p>

<h2>Witnesses Maintain Stories</h2>

<p>Over a dozen people say they saw John Doe #2. Witnesses vary in
details, but agree on certain characteristics: heavy set, dark complected,
tattoos. Witnesses in Junction City and Herington,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ks/">Kansas</a>, say that
they saw John Doe #2 with McVeigh when McVeigh stayed there right before
the bombing. Witnesses in Oklahoma City saw him with McVeigh the morning
of the bombing.</p>

<p>In Junction City, an employee of the Great Western Inn claimed J.D.
checked in three days before the bombing and drove a Ryder truck. Three
guests at the town's Dreamland Motel, where McVeigh stayed for four days,
claimed they saw him outside McVeigh's room. A delivery man claimed
the man was there when he brought Chinese take-out to McVeigh's room.</p>

<p>In Herington, a convenience store clerk remembers McVeigh and J.D.
buying cigarettes. A local who went for gas remembers the same
incident. The owner of a local diner remembers McVeigh, Nichols and J.D.
eating there the morning before the bombing, parking a Ryder truck
and a tan car with Arizona plates outside.</p>

<h2>Conspiracy Theories</h2>

<p>The government's silence about the John Doe #2 suspect has led
many people to offer theories as to the cause of such silence. The
most likely is that any uncertainty on their part will be used by
Timothy McVeigh's defense to help his case.</p>

<p>More extreme speculations are that JD2 was a government informant,
or an agent provacateur who provoked the bombing to justify a
crackdown on militias. While there is currently no evidence for these
ideas, such possibilities are not without precedent in the U.S.,
and the views' prevalence says volumes about the extent of citizens'
distrust of their government.</p>

<hr>

<p>Sources: October 27, 1995 message from
<a href="/revolution/by_name/D/DavidDeming.html">David Deming</a>,
forwarded to Libernet;
October 27, 1995 AP article "Surveillance tape shows shadowy passenger
in Oklahoma City bomb truck," and April 15, 1996 Kansas City <cite>Star</cite>
article, "The search is still on for John Doe No. 2," both reprinted in the
<a href="/revolution/by_name/N/NandO.html">NandO Times</a>.</p>

