<head>
<title>FCC Restricts Cable Companies</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: Act 1992; lawsuit February 22, 1993 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>FCC Restricts "Indecent" Leased-Access Cable</h1>

<p>Among the infringements of the Cable Television Consumer Protection and
Competition Act of 1992 was Section 10, which required cable companies to
restrict "indecency" on leased-access channels.</p>

<p>Indecency is ill-defined, but it is protected in print media by the
First Amendment to the U.S. Constitution. Section 10, however, allows the
FCC to shut down cable companies permanently if they air one program judged
indecent.</p>

<p>Congress mandated that cable companies provide leased-access channels in
1984, and had <em>forbidden</em> cable companies from exercising any control
over content, until the 1992 act, which <em>mandates</em> censorship.</p>

<p>The <a href="/revolution/by_name/A/ACLU.html">ACLU</a> along with several
other organizations filed suit in the U.S. Court of Appeals on February 22,
1993, challenging the new rules as unconstitutional.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: <img src="/images/gopher.gif" alt="[gopher]"><a
href="gopher://gopher.aclu.org:6601/00/newsroom/1993/02_22_93">
ACLU's press release</a> on the lawsuit.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
