<html>
<head>
<title>Harry Browne for President</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Harry Browne for President</h1>

<p>The 1996 <a href="/revolution/by_name/L/LPUS.html">Libertarian Party</a>
national convention nominated author and investment adviser
<a href="/revolution/by_name/B/HarryBrowne.html">Harry Browne</a>
for President of the United States, and entrepreneur
<a href="/revolution/by_name/J/JoJorgensen.html">Jo Jorgensen</a>
for Vice President.</p>

<p>The campaign broke records for the party, setting several milestones
and heading the ticket for the party's <a href="index.html">1996 election
efforts</a>.</p>

<p>Final returns show the Browne/Jorgensen ticket
received 485,120 votes (0.5% of the total). This is the second-best
Libertarian showing ever, falling short only of our
<a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/election/1980/">1980</a> total.
Browne came in fifth, behind Bill Clinton, Bob Dole,
Ross Perot and Ralph Nader.</p>

<p>Browne did best in Arizona, Nevada and Alaska, getting about 1% of
the vote there.</p>

<hr>

<p>Browne <a href="announce.html">announced his candidacy</a> in 1994,
drawing on his following from his books and newsletters for support.
Browne was successfully able to get support from a broader base than
just current party members, with the party and the campaign raising
a record total $3 million in 1996.</p>

<p>Browne <a href="campaigned95.html">campaigned hard in '95</a> for
the party's nomination, visiting state conventions and giving occasional
speeches. Later that year, <cite>Why Government Doesn't Work</cite>
was published, generating significant interest in the campaign.
One of the year's interesting moments was <a href="cityvote.html">City
Vote</a>, a poll intended to focus the campaign on urban issues. Browne
was one of a couple of third-party candidates to qualify for the
ballot, and polled just under one percent.</p>

<p>Browne continued campaigning for the nomination in early 1996,
winning <a href="nhprimary.html">New Hampshire's Libertarian primary</a>
as well as other such contests. Browne handily won the party's nomination
at the national convention held July 4 - 7, 1996 in Washington, D.C.
Unsuccessful candidates for the nomination included
<a href="/revolution/by_name/O/DouglassOhmen.html">Douglass J.  Ohmen</a>,
<a href="/revolution/by_name/S/IrwinSchiff.html">Irwin Schiff</a> and
<a href="/revolution/by_name/T/RickTompkins.html">Rick Tompkins</a>.</p>

<p>Browne then continued a rigorous
full-time campaign, appearing on hundreds of radio talk shows. As
the election neared,
<a href="media.html">media coverage</a> intensified, with appearances on
CNN's Larry King Live, C-SPAN, the Lehrer News Hour, and other news
programs.</p>

<p>Libertarians organized on the Internet very effectively, distributing
campaign news via mailing lists and ganging together to dominate
<img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
href="http://www.coil.com/~ggorka/polls.html">every online poll</a> put on
the web. Net-savvy libertarians also organized
<img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
href="http://home.connectnet.com/qqq/speech/">Stop the Browne-Out</a>,
an independent effort to get Browne included in the debates. While
ultimately unsuccessful, the group did manage to get many journalists,
both online and print, to endorse Browne's inclusion in the debates.
Online political sites <a href="mentions.html">mentioned the party
frequently</a>.</p>

<p>The party achieved 50-state ballot status within a couple of
months of its convention, becoming the first third party ever to accomplish
that feat two presidential elections in a row. Only Clinton, Dole and
Perot were also on all ballots.</p>

<hr>
<h2>Post Mortem</h2>

<p>In December 1996, Browne offered to answer any questions about his
campaign to several online forums. Asking a libertarian for an opinion
is like asking an insurance salesman for a pitch, so he was nearly
inundated with suggestions and questions, most favorable.</p>

<p>Regarding his future plans, Browne said: "I do not know whether I'll
run again in 2000. I can't make that decision until 1999. It will depend
on whether the party is big enough to make a serious run, whether I have
commitments of sufficient funds to be able to begin the campaign with
$1 million in hand and know that it's likely we'll have $30 million or
more for the campaign itself, and whether I still feel young enough to
undertake the task."</p>

<p>In the meantime, he has set up an exploratory committee to start
raising money, has begun a syndicated radio commentary, and is trying
to become part of a lecture bureau to speak on politics at events across
the country.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Campaign Information</h2>

