<head>
<title>Eggert Campaign</title>
<!-- Place: Bethlehem, Connecticut (USA) -->
<!-- Time: 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>George Eggert Campaign</h1>

<p>Mark A. Tuniewicz, Director of Communications of the <a
href="index.html">Libertarian Party of Connecticut</a>,
posted the following message to LPUS on May 3, 1995:<p>

<p>LPCT is pleased to announce the latest in its slate of candidates for the
Fall elections.  Mr. George Eggert, who with his wife MaryAnn recently changed
their party registration to Libertarian, is a former 2-term first selectman in
the town of Bethlehem, <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ct/">Connecticut</a>,
and served 10 years previously as selectman.  A
self-employed 30-year resident, Mr. Eggert will run in a 3 or 4-way race for
his old seat, and will likely be the first elected Connecticut Libertarian.</p>

<p>... Mr. Eggert was obtained as a prospect through the LPCT's quarterly
series of public forums.  The Forums, featuring nationally-know speakers on
topics of general interest, have been useful as both publicity vehicles and to
obtain prospects.  The last two Forums featured a nationally-known inner-city
police chief who came out in favor of drug decriminalization, and the president
of  Education Alternatives, Inc., a MN-based firm to which the management of
the entire Hartford, CT school system was contracted out.</p>

