<html>

<head>
<title>Clipper Chip</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>The Clipper Chip</h1>

<p>The "Clipper Chip" is a general name for a proposal originating in the
Bush administration and pushed by the Clinton administration to establish
a federal encryption standard that includes a "back door" for law
enforcement.</p>

<p>Clipper is actually comprised of several parts:</p>
<ul>
<li>The Skipjack encryption algorithm, which is classified, forms the
basis for the Clipper components.
<li>The Escrowed Encryption Standard (EES) is intended to replace the current
Digital Encryption Standard (DES). EES involves components using the Skipjack
algorithm, with skeleton keys held by federal agencies. Law enforcement
officials (with a warrant of course, trust us) could obtain the escrowed
keys to decrypt any EES-encrypted data.
<li>The Clipper chip itself implements EES for telephones.
<li>The Capstone chip implements EES for computers.
<li>The Tessera card is a PC card containing Capstone.
</ul>

<p>When the Clinton White House announced plans to implement EES, the online
community reacted strongly. As a result, plans for Capstone and Tessera were
put on hold. Although the administration initially said they never intended
to ban other means of encryption, FBI director <a
href="/revolution/by_name/F/LouisFreeh.html">Louis Freeh</a> later said he would
seek such a ban if criminals didn't use EES (duh).</p>

<p>EES met strong online opposition, and several Congressman promised to
block appropriations for EES. After the 1995
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ok/OklahomaCity.html">Oklahoma
City</a>
<a href="/revolution/multi/war/okc/">Federal Building bombing</a>,
reptilian opportunists like Clinton seized the chance to rush through a
Counter-Terrorism Bill, which included funding for Clipper.</p>

<p>To try to rescue the sinking Clipper Chip, U.S. federal agencies
proposed a variation called Commercial Key Escrow, in which private
companies would hold the skeleton keys and provide them to police
when presented with a warrant.</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="announce.html">White House announces Clipper Chip</a></li>
<li><a href="qanda.html">White House's Clipper Q & A</a></li>
<li>Critics of Clipper
	<ul>
	<li><a href="critique.html">A Critique of Clipper</a></li>
	<li><a href="petition.html">CPSR starts anti-Clipper petition</a></li>
	<li><a href="eff.html">EFF opposes Clipper</a></li>
	<li><a href="safire.html">Sink the Clipper Chip</a></li>
	<li><a href="wired.html">Jackboots on the Infobahn</a></li>
	<li>Libertarian Party rejects Clipper in <img src="/images/www.gif"
alt="[WWW]"><a
href="http://www.bradley.edu/campusorg/libertarian/lpdocs/releases/TelephonyAct.html">April
18, 1994 news release</a></li>
	</ul>
<li><a href="ahead.html">Clipper full steam ahead</a></li>
<li><a href="flaws.html">Flaws in the Clipper Chip</a></li>
<li><a href="retreat.html">White House backs down somewhat</a></li>
<li><a href="cke.html">NIST proposes Commercial Key Escrow</a></li>
</ul>

