<head>
<title>Steve Jackson and LP-Texas</title>
<!-- Place: Austin, Texas (USA) -->
<!-- Time: 1993 or 1994 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Steve Jackson and the Libertarian Party</h1>

<p>From <a href="/revolution/by_name/M/JayManifold.html">Jay Manifold</a> of
the Libertarian Party of Texas:</p>

<p>This afternoon I spoke with <a
href="/revolution/by_name/J/SteveJackson.html">Steve Jackson</a>,
proprietor of Steve Jackson
Games in
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/tx/Austin.html">Austin</a>
and plaintiff of a successful lawsuit against the Secret
Service earlier this year.  Mr Jackson's business was ransacked by
Treasury Department goons during the infamous "Hacker Crackdown" of 
1990.  He was already well-known in the "gaming community" and became
familiar to computer users nationwide after this incident.  The trial
was covered in the mainstream press, and the Electronic Frontier 
Foundation assisted in his defense.  He won $50,000 in damages, and each
employee whose private e-mail was read by the Feds after the raid was
awarded $1,000.  For more information about his case, you may wish to
read Bruce Sterling's <cite>The Hacker Crackdown</cite> or almost any recent
issue of <cite>2600</cite> magazine.</p>

<p>Steve, like most of his employees, is a Libertarian. He identifies with us
strongly. Steve offered to assist us with publications, which is his area of
expertise: the games his company publishes involve lengthy hard-copy texts of
rules and scenarios.  His availability is limited, but for certain
one-time-only efforts his assistance may prove invaluable.</p>

<p>One sobering point: in the e-mail message I sent to Steve on Friday to
let him know I'd be calling, I stated: "I believe that your recent
experiences have entailed some of the most egregious violations of
Consitutional rights ever suffered by Texans."  On the phone today, 
Steve said he doesn't agree --- because he's still alive, and they 
didn't burn the place down.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
